<DOC><DOCNO> AP890109-0043 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-09-89 0619EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-09 0610</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0628</SECOND><HEAD>Winter Weather Gives South A Chill; Michigan Bridge Closed</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Moist Gulf of Mexico air in tandem with cold air produced apotpourri of sleet, freezing rain and snow today from the lowerMississippi Valley across the Tennessee Valley to the centralAppalachians.   In Michigan, snow combined with winds up to 60 mph Sunday toreduce visibility on the Mackinac Bridge and forced the MackinacBridge Authority to close the structure to traffic for an hour,authority spokeswoman Lorraine Garries said.   ``We didn't get much accumulation, it was just blowing,'' Garriessaid, adding it was only the third time in 11 years that the bridgewas forced to shut down because of weather.   Snowfall totals across Michigan's upper peninsula ranged up to 13inches, but the lower peninsula had snowfall totaling 1 to 4 inches.   Wet snow fell in parts of Arkansas, Tennessee, Mississippi andAlabama.   It also settled over the central and southern Appalachians where2 to 3 inches of snow accumulated. Up to 6 inches of snow wasexpected in southern West Virginia, with 8 inches over higherelevations.   Winter weather also affected the Northwest today, with snowfalling over eastern parts of the Pacific Northwest, Montana andIdaho. Between 6 and 12 inches of new snow was expected in parts ofIdaho by tonight.   Meanwhile, rain fell along the central Pacific coast.   Strong winds were blowing across the Rockies' east slopes inWyoming and Montana. Winds gusted to 60 mph in the upper YellowstoneRiver Valley in Montana.   Much of the nation's midsection was in the grip of a frigidarctic air mass, with temperatures plummeting below the zero mark inmuch of the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley.   The frigid air was flowing eastward across the warmer waters ofthe lower Great Lakes, creating lake effect snow east of LakeOntario and Lake Erie.   The high Sunday was 86 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla.   Today's forecast called for rain along much of the Pacific coastand extending from the western and central Gulf Coast to Tennesseeand North Carolina; snow across the northern Plateau into thenorthern Rocky Mountains, and in the mid-Atlantic Coast and thesouthern Appalachians; scattered snow showers in the Great Lakesregion; fair to partly sunny skies across the rest of the nation.   Predicted highs: below freezing from the northern and centralRockies through the lower and middle Mississippi Valley to NewEngland; single digits and teens from eastern Montana throughMinnesota and Iowa to the upper Great Lakes; 50 degrees-plus fromthe southern and central coast of California through the Rio GrandeValley of Texas to the southern Atlantic coast, with lower 60s inSouthern California, and 70s and lower 80s in Florida.   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 27 degreesbelow zero at Devils Lake, N.D., to 73 at Miami and Fort Lauderdale,Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 44 cloudy; Boston 38 cloudy; Buffalo 21 snow;Charleston, S.C. 59 fair; Cincinnati 28 cloudy; Cleveland 22 snow;Detroit 16 snow; Miami 69 fair; New York 40 cloudy; Pittsburgh 29cloudy; Portland, Maine 35 windy; Washington 42 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck -16 fair; Chicago 9 partly cloudy; Dallas-FortWorth 35 cloudy; Denver 24 fair; Des Moines 04 fair; Indianapolis 23cloudy; Kansas City 15 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul -10 fair;Nashville 35 snow; New Orleans 53 cloudy; St. Louis 23 cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 15 fair; Anchorage 22 partly cloudy; Las Vegas30 fair; Los Angeles 44 fair; Phoenix 36 fair; Salt Lake City 24cloudy; San Diego 42 fair; San Francisco 47 drizzle; Seattle 47cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 23 windy; Toronto 18 snow.</TEXT></DOC>